---
import SiteLayout from "../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";
---

<SiteLayout
  title="Bivariate Quantitative Bayesian LASSO"
  description="A bivariate Bayesian LASSO framework for detecting rare haplotype associations with two correlated continuous phenotypes."
>
  <section class="p-8 sm:p-12 md:p-16 lg:p-24">
    <div class="max-w-8xl">

      {/* Hero */}
      <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-gray-900">
        Bivariate Quantitative Bayesian LASSO
      </h1>

      <p class="mt-4 text-lg text-gray-700">
        A statistical framework for detecting association of rare haplotypes with two correlated continuous phenotypes, leveraging Bayesian shrinkage
        to improve power in low-frequency settings.
      </p>

      <div class="mt-4 flex flex-wrap gap-x-6 gap-y-2 text-sm text-gray-600">
        <span><strong>Status:</strong> Published</span>
        <span>
          <strong>Role:</strong> PhD candidate (supervised by Dr. Swati Biswas)
        </span>
        <a
          href="https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/genetics/articles/10.3389/fgene.2023.1104727/full"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="font-medium underline"
        >
          Journal article
        </a>
      </div>

      {/* At a glance */}
      <div class="mt-10 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4 text-sm">
        <div><strong>Domain:</strong> Statistical genetics / rare variant association</div>
        <div><strong>Setting:</strong> Rare haplotype association test</div>
        <div><strong>Outcome:</strong> Two correlated continuous phenotypes</div>
        <div><strong>Methods:</strong> Bayesian LASSO, shrinkage priors, MCMC</div>
        <div><strong>Deliverable:</strong> New association test + empirical evaluation</div>
      </div>

      {/* Background */}
      <div class="mt-12">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">Background</h2>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 text-gray-700">
          <li>
            Many complex traits are correlated; analyzing them jointly can improve efficiency and power.
          </li>
          <li>
            Standard single-phenotype tests may miss signals that become clearer under joint modeling.
          </li>
          <li>
            Lack of haplotype-based association test that can handle multiple correlated continuous phenotypes.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      {/* Methods */}
      <div class="mt-10">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">Methods</h2>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 text-gray-700">
          <li>
            Regularizing the regression coefficients removes unassociated haplotypes.
          </li>
          <li>
            Utilized latent variable to model correlation between two continuous phenotypes.
          </li>
          <li>
            Carried out extensive simulations to investigate the performance of bivariate QBL and compare it with that of a standard (univariate) haplotype association test, Haplo.score.
          </li>
          <li>
            Evaluated operating characteristics using simulation studies (type I error, power) across diverse rare-haplotype scenarios.
          </li>
          <li>
            Demonstrated utility through application to Genetic Analysis Workshop (GAW) 19 exome sequencing data on systolic and diastolic blood pressures.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      {/* Results */}
<div class="mt-10">
  <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">Results</h2>

  <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-12 gap-6 items-start">
    {/* Left: bullets */}
    <div class="lg:col-span-6">
      <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 text-gray-700">
        <li>
          Maintained appropriate type I error control across a range of simulated settings.
        </li>
        <li>
          Showed improved power over Haplo.score across diverse scenarios with rare haplotype effects and correlated phenotypes.
        </li>
        <li>
          Produced interpretable effect estimates under shrinkage, supporting stable inference in low-frequency contexts.
        </li>
        <li>
          Detected several rare haplotypes associated with systolic and diastolic blood pressure phenotypes in GAW 19.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    {/* Right: image */}
    <div class="lg:col-span-6">
      <figure class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-gray-100 p-3 shadow-sm">
        <img
          src="/images/BivariateQBL.png"
          alt="biQBL simulation and real-data results"
          class="w-full h-auto rounded-md"
          loading="lazy"
        />
        <figcaption class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-600 text-center">
          Figure: Simulation results under sample size 500, setting 1 (6 haplotypes, both β = 1), and  ρ = 0.1.
        </figcaption>
      </figure>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>


      {/* Takeaways */}
      <div class="mt-10">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">Takeaways</h2>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 text-gray-700">
          <li>
            Bivariate QBL is an important addition to the existing genetic association tests.
          </li>
          <li>
            Bayesian shrinkage offers materially improved detection of rare genetic signals.
          </li>
          <li>
            Bivariate QBL provides a practical framework for multivariate haplotype association in statistical genetics.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      {/* Citation */}
      <div class="mt-12 text-sm text-gray-600">
        <strong>Citation:</strong><br />
        <strong>IH Sajal</strong> and S. Biswas (2023).
        <em>
          Bivariate Quantitative Bayesian LASSO for Detecting Association of Rare Haplotypes with Two Correlated Continuous Phenotypes.
        </em>
        Frontiers in Genetics, 14.
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>
</SiteLayout>
